NEWCASTLE DISEASE - CYPRUS (03): (FAMAGUSTA) POULTRY, SPREAD
************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Mon 9 Sep 2013
Source: The Poultry Site [edited]
http://www.thepoultrysite.com/poultrynews/29997/further-newcastle-disease-confirmed-in-cyprus


Authorities have confirmed a further outbreak of Newcastle disease in laying hens in the village of Vrysoulles.

Notification was [submitted] by the Cyprus Veterinary Services in Nicosia on Fri 6 Sep 2013; 113 chickens were declared 'susceptible'. All birds have subsequently been destroyed. Initially, 83 cases were recorded with 80 birds dying as a result of infection. The chickens were in a backyard holding; APMV-1 was isolated on 3 Sep 2013. The outbreak was in the east of the country in Ammochostos [Famagusta].

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The information above is derived from Cyprus' OIE follow-up report no 5 on Newcastle disease (NCD), available with map at http://www.oie.int/wahis_2/public/wahid.php/Reviewreport/Review?page_refer=MapFullEventReport&reportid=14033.

This outbreak, in the village Vrysoulles, Ammochostos [Famagusta] district, affected a backyard holding which consisted of 113 laying hens and broilers. There were 83 clinical cases of which 80 died. The remaining 33 birds were destroyed. The causative agent, APMV-1, was isolated on 3 Sep 2013.

Since the start of the Cyprus NCD epizootic, in June 2013, there have been 15 outbreaks, including a total of 251 970 susceptible birds with 61 929 clinical NCD cases of which 61 840 died. The remaining 190 130 birds have been destroyed. The current OIE summary of the epizootic with a map is available at http://www.oie.int/wahis_2/temp/reports/en_fup_0000014033_20130906_161116.pdf.

Vrysoulles is situated adjacent to the Turkish-held territory of Northern Cyprus; map at http://www.fallingrain.com/world/CY/01/Vrysoules.html. Coordination between the veterinary authorities in both parts of Cyprus is essential.

The outbreak is termed "continuing". - Mod.AS

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: http://healthmap.org/r/8nk1.]
